Foxes aren’t head-on animals. Even when attacking prey, they stalk and judge from a distance and avoid fights with other animals as much as possible. They’re extremely skittish as well, I remember an animal rescuer saying something along the lines of, “if I moved my arm in any manner that comes off as unexpected, the fox would bolt across the enclosure.” Heavily paraphrased, but you get the idea.

In terms of love, it varies heavily. Some foxes never let humans get close to them, others revel in the attention humans bring them. Some foxes only get excited around one or two humans, and others can be very social. It depends on their personality, but those two are the most common reactions to humans I’ve seen. Also foxes seem to be rather loud, regardless of who’s in their presence.

I’d imagine anthro foxes would be rather shy and distant to most people, only coming out of their shell after getting to know them. And to people they grow close to, they’d become not only more loving, but also more mischievous and playful. Some foxes may act like an excited dog when their human comes home. Others may act more reserved; loving, but hands off most of the time.

Also this only applies to most true fox species. Others, for example grey foxes, are just as skittish, but pretty quiet and distant most of the time. It varies if you want to account for all fox species.

Sorry, I’ve spent too much time researching foxes and I have all this information in my head with nowhere else to dump.

I agree with what >>36235623 said. An elevator pitch should, at the very least, give some idea of who the characters are and what the conflict of the story is. All that blurb really says, in fewer words, is "Wizard guy explores weird tower."

Here's the thing: no one cares about super in-depth worldbuilding or whatever fantasy tropes you're playing with. When people are looking for something to read, they're still going to want some hint of what they're in for in regards to characters and conflict. Everything else is just spice added to build on that foundation.

Again, as the other guy said, what's the
"So what?" Who's in it? What's happening in it? Where's it going? You gotta give potential readers something to care about, otherwise they won't.

>>36236235
Just weighing in, but one thing that strikes me about your pitch is the heavy use of in-universe names. Those don't really mean anything for us, because we're completely unfamiliar with the setting and story. And while you're giving us information, you're also trying to get information from us, so you need to tailor what you say to that. If you want us to tell you if something sounds interesting the what and why is more important than us knowing a name. I think this goes hand in hand with popular advice a lot of new writers get these days, which is to try and hook your readers in early.

Ultimately, people here will be looking for a few things: Style and genre of the story, (potential) relationship between characters, and of course what drives the story.

One of the things that I find useful at some point is to have four things.
An outline, a plot summary, a blurb (no more than 150 words!), and a pitch I could say in 15 seconds or less. I usually work in that order, but having a working blurb and/or pitch might be a good way to say focused if you're more a pantser. I pants like hell, but only after I have an outline.
Think of your blurb as being the voiceover for a movie trailer. Your pitch is the stinger at the end, or what is on the movie poster.
Take the classic scifi horror movie, Alien. In space, no one can hear you scream. State an obvious fact of physics, and combined with the title answers the obvious question of why you would scream in space. Remember that at that time (1979), Star Wars and its rather safe aliens were front & center in the human consciousness. Second point blank message: we're not Star Wars.

Best of luck. We don't become better writers by not following our ideas.
